column9:
A 40-45 years old guy sitting right next to me on 'Nepal Yatayat' was typing vulgar things on his phone and trying to show me his phone screen. When I didn't pay any attention to him, he was trying to push me and was stretching his elbow and trying to touch me. I was super mad. Then, when he got off at his station, he tried to touch my shoulders. Then, I could resist no more and yelled 'Sir, make sure your hands are in right place not here and there in a crowded bus like this.' Then everyone was like asking me what happened and assuming what might have happened everyone on bus were yelling at him when he quickly got out of bus without even looking back.
That incident was terrible but I liked the way everyone reacted and were against harassment.

column9:
I have gotten used to verbal and sexual harassment.

How terrible of a sentence is that?! Nobody should ever, ever get "used" to things like that. The first time I admitted it to myself, I couldn't stop thinking about it. Is this what the world has come to? Little girls or boys who haven't even had the chance to blow out their 16th birthday cake candles are already used to harassment. 

But like most females in Nepal, I have. Verbal teasing and unwanted looks are things that I don't go a day without facing, and I say this with no exaggeration. Molestation has happened so many times you can't count it on 5 fingers. It's gotten to a state where I have an actual routine prepared for these things. And that fact, even though it is about me, shocks me. Because that doesn't mean this is only happening to me, thousands of other females in Nepal are just like me. And -that- shocks me. 

But the part that truly enrages me, leaved my face, neck and ears red, is when people defend these acts. 

"Boys will be boys." 

"Maybe it was because of what you were wearing." Even in the coldest of winters when I'm dressed from head to toe, in bulky clothing, eve teasing still takes place. And even if I wasn't, even if I -was- wearing revealing clothing, that does not justify the actions at all.

"You're an early bloomer, after all." Oh I'm sorry, should I be wearing super tight sports bras and binders 24/7, which will ruin my ribs and lungs and overall body, just in hopes that the verbal and sexual will decrease? Because let's be honest, it can never completely stop, right?

I've become a hunchback, a "kupri", I experience back pain as an old lady would, even though I haven't even reached the age where people call you "the youth", and do you know why? Because ever since I was ten I'd try to conceal my boobs, and hunching your back will do that. Every time a relative I haven't seen for a long time comes over "How have you become kupri, you weren't when you were little." And I just laugh along, but in my head I have to deal with the extremely saddening fact that I have ruined my back just because of a little girl having to go through harassment.

column9: I remember like it was yesterday,everyday after returning home from school, for years , there would be groups of boys. It literally started from the front of my high school, all the way to getting home. My mom told me to look in the road if anyone said mean or sexually things. I was never taught to fight back. I guess I was made to believe that it was me who was the problem, and I was initiating the catcalls. After all these years, I will not forget an incident in holi where this guy touched me inappropriately. It made me scared to walk in a road where I lived for 10 years. It was something That I will never be able to forget.

I agreed. But at that moment, he was trying to touch my genitals. I had no idea what was going on at that time. But as I grew older, I understood what he was trying to do. This incident still creeps me out. 

My second case of harrassment was when I was in class 10.I was returning home after giving the sent-up examination. In the bus, I was constantly being touched by a person behind me. I was also constantly being pressed upon by him. I was praying to God to end that moment. I was praying for that man to get off the bus, so that I would feel easy. It was a horrible horrible experience.

column9: Being catcalled while walking around town alone or even as a group of girls has almost become the norm. There have been two instances when I have been sexually touched while walking alone on the streets, one when I was 11 and the other when I was 14-15. As ive grown older, I've  learned to become more straightforward and unafraid of such men and stare directly at them and tell them exactly what I'm thinking or just throw up the middle finger and a dirty look.

I was at the turning right before Patan Durbar Square, borad daylight, crowded street, a man is sitting on a bike, eyes me head to toe, and whistles. He's still staring at my legs and says "ohooo tyesto ramro khutta tah chopera hidnu hudaina hai!" My blood is boiling but I'm also scared, so i gibe him a stare--dead in the eye until he looks away. 
I feel that giving a glare and not looking away until they're uncomfortable helps a lot. It's saved me from verbal harassment most of the time because the men are uncomfortable by the time they've checked me out and glared at my stares for an uncomfortably long period.

column9:
Alot has happened,  especially being touched in public transportations and yet being unsure if the person truly meant it or it was by mistake. I felt that when I was young. Now I know that most of them were intentional and I never should have been ashamed of it.
My latest encounter was when I was sending off my younger cousins including my 12 year old sister. As I waved them bye a guy replied to them saying Goo..od byyeeeee.....!!
I was so enraged at him. Most people might still say he didn't do anything or say anything wrong. That is what's wrong with us. We wait for something to happen. The guy started with cat calling and teasing and move on to bolder things. While I had been a follower of Ignorance is Bliss, not anymore.
The perverted look on that guy's face when he looked at my sisters ignited this fire in me that I won't ignore it anymore and neither should you.  Make noise, make alot of noise. Put that guy, boy or man im his place no matter the age.

column9:
One time a person, when I was 21 followed me from my bus-stop to home, continuously asking my name, number, if I had a Facebook. I completely ignored then, they started getting angry, luckily I had reached my home area.
Next day, another guy again followed me and asked my name when I refused to give him, he said "It's just a matter of time till I find your name". Though I have never seen him since.
When I was 11 years old, I am one of those girls whose puberty came earlier. So, my cousin used to fondle my breasts but when I told my mom about it, he stopped it. I don't know whether my parents talked to him or not.
Another of my distant cousin always used to touch me in thighs when I was 10 years old, used to show me pornographic videos, though I always tried to stay away from him. So, whenever he was at our house, I used to stay close to my mom. He used to show me penis of those naked babas who come at Pashupati during Shivaratri, though I refused to see them, he used to catch me off guard. Luckily my little brother used to be with me and even he used to say, "Don't show her!"
At the grocery shop that's staying on rent at my house, when I went to it when I was 9 years old to buy something.But the owner tried to lure me by giving me cold drinks and then started touching  me in inappropriate places. I felt uncomfortable, finished my drink fast and ran from there.
So, yes, there is sexual predators all around you even your own home and society. I learned early to be careful and take care of myself. But, I still can't forget those times.

column3: Streets, Public Transportations, while taking lift during the India-Nepal Blockade

column9:
People just stare inappropriately while in the public bus and when its crowded try to touch taking the advantage of the crowded bus.
One time while India-Nepal Blockade, it was 7pm  and the carpooling was at high ly chosen option. I also chose to take a lift at RNAC. My home was 30 minutes far and with bike it can take only 10minutes. So the motorcyclists and I were talking and going. Just some simple conversations. Then on the way there was a place where there was a bit of dark. He began to touch my legs .I told him to stop there and then. But he didn't stop. Then he advanced his hands towards backwards again and touched my thighs. I screamed he told me not to.Then I lied to him that my father is a DIG then he halted. I jumped off his bike and ran away. Crying and crying. I didn't stop till I was near my home and even didn't look back. I didn't had guts to tell to anyone at home. I just cried all night and promised myself never to take a lift from strangers. Even if I remember now I shiver. :'(

column9: I often feel the harassment when I am in a public  transportation. It is very difficult for us travel in public transportation because in a micro with a limited seat of 15 passengers, we are bound to travel with more than 35 passengers. In such a crowd, usually boys tend to get physical and look very sexually upon us. There must be a proper laws on public transportation on how much passenger they can take along on a trip based on the transportation capacity. In the similar way, girls often do not feel safe to travel alone in the streets at night. There are no light poles in streets, even if it has, the bulbs are not working and in dismay, the streets are always darker. Plus there are no policemen at the inside roads, however there must be a security system given by the state at night. Its their duty to protect the citizens, A security booth must be there in every place inorder to watch the activity that takes place.

column9:
1. Well, I was walking in the busy street of Asan with my mom and aunt. A man just passed by me very close and he tried to grab my butt and he almost did. To this my immediate action was i just hit him with the umbrella I was holding that too very hard. He just ran away like a beaten dog.

2. The most unsafe place is the local buses and vehicle, this was back then when i traveled a lot using public transport. The men especially the middle aged men are more into touching or trying to touch wherever possible.
Even though it looked it was just a dash due to the brake kicked by the driver. But the uneasiness is there when so did happen and you know one can feel or sense the intention of these kind of men.

Recently, last summers while I was boarding a bus a group of young boys probably 16-17 yr old cat called and I screamed at them and when I confronted them they said no they had no intentions of teasing me.

column9: I was walking out of Thamel with my boyfriend to go to our car after having dinner at a restaurant. He walked a few paces ahead of me and within that split second three men walking towards us surrounded me and one of them grabbed my vagina. It was so traumatizing. I ran to my boyfriend and started crying uncontrollably. This is also not the first or sadly last time this will happen but I refuse of be a victim. Nowadays, I call out perpetrators on their actions.

column9:
Im a tenth grader fairly aged 15 years. I have a couple of experiences of hassresment in the streets which were mostly verbal but the most vauge memory I have is about a year old when I was followed. 
As usual I was returning back after a swim at Greenwich hotel. I had my swimming dress on which was a halter short dress. While returning I intended to take the longer route back home to treat me with some icecream.
The restaurant next to the icecream parlour happened to have a dance party and there were a lot of boys leaning against their motorcycle and smoking. I could hear verbal comments being passed, I wasnt afraid instead I  reply, "respect chaina?" As I was always taught to fight for my dignity and didnt believe in being a typical Nepali girl who would ignore like nothing happened. 
I treated myself and was returning back when the guys followed me. Nervousness hit me. I was already imagining things that could happen. I was caught in surprise when the guy had the guts to pull my hand and offer a ride, denying with I'm not a normal Nepali girl attitude I told them id call the police if they came any closer and ran to the nearest shop and called over someone to pick me up. 
I wasnt able to share this with my family as they would restrict my freedom. The only change that occurred was that of me being uncomfortable and not confident enough to fight back when someone verbally harasses me, like the old times.
